<paragraph blockId="67.[151,1437,224,2015]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
This new species runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Melander in Wilcox" authorityName="Melander in Wilcox" box="[477,830,1736,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Cyrtopogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversus">
<emphasis box="[477,602,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">C. inversus</emphasis>
Melander in Wilcox
</taxonomicName>
&amp; Martin’s (1936) key. The latter species is easily distinguished as the males have black setae on the antennal segments and the pronotum has white setae. The abdomen of the female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melander in Wilcox" box="[333,458,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Cyrtopogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversus">
<emphasis box="[333,458,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">C. inversus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is almost completely covered with black setae and lacks the gray pollinose fascia on the sixth tergite. The species is named in honor of Dr. Frank 
<collectingCountry box="[788,878,1844,1870]" name="Netherlands" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Holland</collectingCountry>
who has provided a number of new distributional records for Wyoming robber flies as well as collecting part of the 
<typeStatus box="[888,936,1881,1907]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">type</typeStatus>
series.
</paragraph>
